Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
setPGPinUseSignalRoute(25.10)                    setPGPinUseSignalRoute(25.10)

Name
       setPGPinUseSignalRoute  -  Sets  the  internal bit for a given cell/pin
       pair to be routed by the signal router

Syntax
        setPGPinUseSignalRoute

       [-off]

       [-all]

       cellPins cellName:pinName cellName:pinName2 ...

       [-well]

       Sets the internal bit for a given cell/pin pair to  be  routed  by  the
       signal router. Use this command to enable NanoRoute to route always-on-
       pins in SRPG (state retention power gating) or always-on buffer cells.

Parameters
       -all   Routes all backup and non-main_rail primary power/ground pins.

              Type: Boolean, Optional

       cellPins <cellName:pinName>

       * <cellName>:Specifies  the  cell  containing  the pin for NanoRoute to
         route. You can use a wildcard to specify all cells of certain type.

       * <pinName>:Specifies the pin name  of  the  secondary  PG  pin  to  be
         routed.

       -off
         Unsets  this  feature  for  the  specified  list of cellPins or cell-
         Name:pinName.

       -well
         Includes nwell and pwell pins.

         Type: Boolean, Optional

Examples
              * The following commands set both the vddo and vsso pins for the
                signal router, but NanoRoute will only route vddo:

                setPGPinUseSignalRoute SDRFF:vddo SDRFF:vsso

                routePGPinUseSignalRoute -nets VDD

              * The following command sets NanoRoute to route the VDD1 pin  of
                all NAND cells:

                setPGPinUseSignalRoute NAND*:VDD1

              * The  following  command unsets NanoRoute to route the VDD1 pin
                of all the NAND cells, which were set earlier:

                setPGPinUseSignalRoute NAND*:VDD1 -off

